namedLocations.description: A payment is the trade of value from one party (such as a person or company) to another for goods, or services, or to fulfill a legal obligation. Payment can take a large variety of forms. Barter, the exchange of one good or service for another, is a form of payment. The most common means of payment involve use of money, cheque, or debit, credit or bank transfers. Payments may also take complicated forms, such as stock issues or the transfer of anything of value or benefit to the parties. In US law, the payer is the party making a payment while the payee is the party receiving the payment. In trade, payments are frequently preceded by an invoice or bill.

transcript.text: Hello, welcome to the on Print Shop store management tutorial series.
In today's video we will talk about managing store inventory.
The inventory option allows private store customers to place orders with large printing quantities when they don't want all printing quantities to be shipped at one time.
The private store customers can raise the request for the required product quantity as per their needs from available product quantities while placing the order.
So let's see how it works or how we can configure it in admin.
In the Admin panel, navigate to the Store Management section and then click on the Stores menu.
Select the store from the listing.
Click on the Actions drop down and select the Configuration option.
You will find a widget for managing store inventory in the Configuration tab.
Click on the Inventory widget.
In the popup.
You will see all the products that are assigned to this store.
Now let's enter the inventory details for the business card product.
Let's enter 2500 in the minimum print quantity.
This is the minimum required product quantity at order time.
To allow the inventory option for shipment requests, you need to enter a minimum shipping quantity such as 1000.
Enter the cost for the per printing unit here such as 0.01.
If there will be any shipment handling cost for each shipment request, then enter the charges here such as $15.
Lastly, in the storage days, you have to enter the maximum number of days.
In this example, let's enter 90 here.
So till 90 days the inventory will be stored and after that it will be automatically discarded.
Once you have defined all the details, click on the save.
Now let's see how it works at the front end when the customer places the order on the product page.
When the customer selects to customize the business card, designs the product, and clicks on continue, it will be redirected to the product additional info page.
On this page, if you see 500 quantities are selected and if you choose yes for inventory, the system will not allow it because the minimum threshold of 2500 printing quantities is mandatory.

Now if you select 2500 quantities, then the inventory option will work and the system will display the preconfigured 1000 quantities in the shipment quantities field and $15 as the shipment handling cost.
You can change this amount, but it should be between 1000 to 2500.
You can verify the total amount and then proceed with the checkout.
On the next page, verify the payment details and then place the order.
To view the order details, click on the view details and then click on the Inventory tab.
Here you can review that the order has been placed for the 1000 quantities and for the remaining quantities, the customer will have the option to place the order.
So whenever the customer visits the same page next time, he can ask for the remaining quantities and click the continue button.
If we talk about the order details in the admin panel, the details will be displayed under the inventory tab.
This was all about how you can manage the product inventory in your private stores.
If you have any questions, our support executives are here to help.
Just reach out through live chat on on printshop.com.
Thanks for tuning in.
